/* STREAMING_CHUNK: Adding a dense chapter writing block... */{"messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Write Chapter 1: The Ascent for our alpine gothic project at workspace/alpine-gothic/chapter-001.md. Ensure it is highly atmospheric, sensory, and introduces the mountain setting with rich detail."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "<tool_call>\n{"name": "write", "args": {"path": "workspace/alpine-gothic/chapter-001.md", "content": "# Chapter 1: The Ascent\n\nThe iron cable car hung suspended in a vast, grey void, humming with a low-frequency vibration that resonated through the soles of Julian Vance's leather boots. Outside, the world had ceased to exist. The valley floor, with its orderly pine forests and silver ribbons of mountain streams, had been swallowed an hour ago by the climbing mist. Now, there was only the damp, clinging fog and the periodic, metallic clink-clack of the suspension carriage passing over the support pylons.\n\nJulian drew his wool coat closer around his shoulders. The air inside the cabin was freezing, smelling faintly of ancient grease, wet iron, and something else—a sweet, cloying aroma that reminded him of overripe peaches rotting under autumn leaves. He coughed, a dry, rasping rattle that seemed to echo too loudly against the glass panes.\n\nFrom the gloom above, a massive, jagged silhouette began to take form. It did not look like a place of healing. The Ridge Sanatorium was a sprawling, multi-tiered structure of dark granite and rotting pine timber, clinging to the basalt cliffs like a parasite to an open wound. Its windows, narrow and spaced like the arrow slits of an old fortress, stared blankly out into the abyss. A few panes caught the sickly, pale glow of interior oil lamps, flickering like dying stars behind curtains of grey ice.\n\nWhen the cable car finally shuddered to a halt in the wooden docking bay, the silence of the high ridge rushed in to meet him. It was a heavy, suffocating silence, broken only by the rhythmic, mechanical sighing of the valley wind passing through the roof shingles. Sister Clara stood waiting on the wooden platform, her wool habit damp with condensation. She held an iron lantern, its yellow flame casting long, dancing shadows across her pale face. She did not smile as Julian stepped onto the wet planks; she merely looked at his medical bag with a quiet, knowing gaze."}}\n</tool_call>"}, {"role": "user", "content": "System Tool Result:\n{"success": true}"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "Chapter 1 has been drafted and written to workspace/alpine-gothic/chapter-001.md. The atmosphere establishes the isolation of the ridge and introduces Sister Clara."}]}
